    correctAnswer: 3,
    explanation: "UCC §3-104 negotiability requirements: (1) In writing, (2) Signed by maker (note) or drawer (draft/check), (3) Unconditional promise or order, (4) Fixed amount of money, (5) Payable on demand or at a definite time, (6) Payable to order or bearer (words of negotiability), (7) No additional unauthorized undertaking. No notarization is required. If any element is missing, the instrument is non-negotiable (still enforceable as a contract, but holder-in-due-course status is not available).",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - A negotiable instrument must be in writing and signed by the maker (for a note) or the drawer (for a draft or check) to be valid; this signifies the maker's or drawer's intent to be bound by the instrument.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - A negotiable instrument must be payable either on demand (immediately) or at a definite time in the future, and it must contain words of negotiability, such as 'payable to order' or 'payable to bearer,' indicating it can be transferred.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - The promise or order to pay must be unconditional, meaning it cannot be subject to any other agreement or condition, and it must be for a fixed amount of money, allowing for easy determination of the instrument's value.",
      3: "Why option D is CORRECT - Notarization is not a requirement for negotiability under UCC Article 3. While notarization can add an extra layer of authentication in some legal contexts, it's not necessary for an instrument to be considered negotiable.",
    },
