    options: ["The CPA must have committed fraud","Any person who reads the financial statements can sue","Only the client has standing to sue","The third party is a member of a limited group whose reliance the CPA knew or should have known (foreseen class)"],
    correctAnswer: 3,
    explanation: "Three approaches to CPA liability to third parties for negligence: (1) Ultramares (privity) — only those in privity or near privity (most restrictive), (2) Restatement §552 (foreseen users/class) — liability extends to persons the CPA knows will rely, or a limited class whose reliance is foreseen (e.g., a bank the CPA knows will receive the financial statements) — most widely adopted, (3) Foreseeable users — liability to all reasonably foreseeable users (most expansive, minority). For fraud: all three approaches allow any injured party to sue. Under Restatement, CPA must have known of or intended for the specific third party (or limited group) to rely.",
