    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Under §1367, an S corporation shareholder's stock basis is adjusted annually: INCREASES: (1) ordinary business income (pro rata share); (2) separately stated income items (capital gains, §1231 gains, tax-exempt interest, etc.); (3) additional capital contributions; (4) the excess of deduction for depletion over basis of property. DECREASES (in order): (1) distributions (not included in income); (2) nondeductible, noncapital expenses (fines, penalties, 50% of meals, life insurance premiums); (3) depletion deduction; (4) ordinary losses and separately stated loss items. Important distinctions from partnerships: S corporation shareholders do NOT increase basis for corporate-level debt (unlike partners who include their share of partnership liabilities in basis). Only loans made directly FROM the shareholder TO the corporation create \"debt basis\" that allows additional loss deductions.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Nondeductible expenses decrease a shareholder's basis, not increase it. These expenses reduce the amount the shareholder can recover tax-free.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - Ordinary income, separately stated income items, and capital contributions all represent an increase in the shareholder's investment in the S corporation. These items increase the amount the shareholder can receive tax-free upon disposition of their stock.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Distributions to shareholders reduce their stock basis. Distributions are essentially a return of capital, decreasing the shareholder's investment.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Unlike partnerships, S corporation shareholders generally do not increase their stock basis for corporate-level debt. Only direct loans from the shareholder to the S corporation create debt basis.",
    },
    educational: "An S corporation shareholder's stock basis is crucial for determining gain or loss upon the sale of stock and the deductibility of losses passed through from the corporation. Basis is increased by contributions and income items, and decreased by distributions and losses, ensuring that income and losses are only taxed once at the shareholder level.",
    examTip: "Remember the order of basis adjustments: increases first, then distributions, then nondeductible expenses, and finally losses. This order matters for loss deductibility!",
    memoryAid: "I-CAL-D: Increases, Capital Contributions, Additions, Losses, Distributions (for basis adjustments)",
    reference: "IRC §1367",
