    explanation: "Under §706(b), a partnership must adopt a tax year determined by a tiered approach: (1) Majority interest year — the tax year of partners owning more than 50% of partnership capital and profits (if they have the same year-end); (2) if no majority interest year exists — the year of all \"principal partners\" (partners with 5%+ interest); (3) if principal partners have different years — the year that results in the \"least aggregate deferral\" (a mathematical calculation); (4) §444 election — the partnership may elect a fiscal year that produces no more than 3 months of deferral, but must make required payments (§7519) — essentially an interest-free deposit with the IRS. This rule prevents income deferral by using a partnership year-end different from the partners' year-end. Form 1065 is due on March 15 (for calendar-year partnerships).",
