    explanation: "The AAA is a corporate-level account (not shareholder-specific) that tracks cumulative S corporation income: (1) PURPOSE — identifies distributions that are from previously-taxed S corporation income (tax-free) versus accumulated C corporation E&P (taxable dividends); (2) INCREASES — S corporation ordinary income and separately stated income items (but NOT tax-exempt income — that goes to OAA, the Other Adjustments Account); (3) DECREASES — distributions, losses and deductions, nondeductible expenses (but NOT federal taxes related to C corporation years); (4) AAA CAN go negative (unlike stock basis, which cannot go below zero); (5) AAA is CRITICAL for S corporations with accumulated E&P from prior C corporation years — the distribution ordering rules under §1368(c) allocate distributions first to AAA, then to accumulated E&P, then to remaining AAA, then to stock basis/capital gain.",
