    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Under IRC §542, a corporation is a personal holding company if: (1) more than 50% of the value of its outstanding stock is owned (directly or by attribution under §544) by 5 or fewer individuals at any time during the last half of the taxable year, AND (2) at least 60% of its adjusted ordinary gross income for the taxable year is personal holding company income. PHC income includes dividends, interest, rents (if less than 50% of AOGI), royalties, and personal service contracts. The PHC tax is 20% of undistributed PHC income.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - While 50% is a key threshold for stock ownership in determining PHC status, the income threshold is higher.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - A corporation is a personal holding company if more than 50% of its stock is owned by 5 or fewer individuals AND at least 60% of its adjusted ordinary gross income (AOGI) is personal holding company (PHC) income.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - 75% is not the correct income threshold for determining personal holding company status; the threshold is lower.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - The income threshold for PHC status is lower than 80% of adjusted ordinary gross income.",
    },
    educational: "Personal Holding Company (PHC) rules prevent individuals from using corporations to shelter passive income. If a corporation is deemed a PHC, it may be subject to a special tax on its undistributed PHC income, discouraging this type of tax avoidance.",
    examTip: "Remember the 60% income test for PHCs; it's a common distractor on the exam, often confused with other percentage tests.",
    memoryAid: "Think of '60%' as 'Sixty Percent Holds Cash' - reminding you of the income test for PHCs holding cash-generating assets.",
    reference: "IRC §§541-547",
