    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "In a like-kind exchange, if the taxpayer is relieved of a larger mortgage than assumed, the net debt relief is treated as boot received. Here, the taxpayer transferred a $200,000 mortgage (relief) and assumed a $150,000 mortgage, resulting in net mortgage boot of $50,000 ($200,000 − $150,000). This $50,000 of boot triggers gain recognition equal to the lesser of the boot or the realized gain. The taxpayer could offset mortgage boot by paying additional cash — cash given can offset mortgage boot received (but mortgage boot given cannot offset cash boot received under the netting rules of Treas. Reg. §1.1031(b)-1).",
