    educational: "Agency law dictates that an agent can only bind a principal when acting within their authority. Authority can be express (explicitly granted), implied (reasonably inferred), or apparent (based on the principal's actions leading a third party to believe authority exists). If an agent acts outside their authority, the principal is generally not bound unless they ratify the agent's actions.",
    examTip: "Carefully analyze the scope of the agent's authority as defined in the question; look for limiting phrases like 'at listed prices'.",
