      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Express authority is directly granted to the agent by the principal, either orally or in writing. In this scenario, the agent exceeded their authority, meaning no express authority existed for that specific action.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Apparent authority exists when the principal leads a third party to reasonably believe that the agent has authority, even if the agent doesn't actually possess it. Here, the focus is on the principal's *subsequent* acceptance, not on prior representations to a third party.",
