    explanation: "Agency requires: mutual consent (express or implied), agent acts on behalf of principal, principal has right to control. No consideration required - gratuitous agency is valid. Writing required only for specific situations (Statute of Frauds).",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Registration with state authorities is generally not required to establish an agency relationship. Certain industries or specific types of agents (e.g., real estate agents) may require registration, but this is not a universal requirement for all agency relationships.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - Agency relationships are fundamentally based on agreement; both the principal and the agent must consent to the relationship. This mutual consent, whether express or implied, forms the basis of the agent's authority to act on behalf of the principal.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Consideration, such as payment of compensation, is not a necessary element for the creation of an agency relationship. A gratuitous agency, where the agent acts without compensation, is perfectly valid.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - While a written contract is advisable for clarity and to avoid disputes, it is not always required. The Statute of Frauds dictates when a contract must be in writing to be enforceable, and this applies to agency agreements only in specific situations, such as when the agency relationship cannot be completed within one year.",
    },
    educational: "An agency relationship is created when one person (the principal) delegates authority to another person (the agent) to act on their behalf and subject to their control. The agent's actions bind the principal, creating legal obligations. The key elements are consent, control, and acting on behalf of the principal; consideration and a written agreement are not always required.",
    examTip: "Focus on the core elements of agency: consent, control, and acting on behalf of the principal. Eliminate answer choices that introduce unnecessary requirements like consideration or a written agreement in all cases.",
    memoryAid: "CCA - Consent, Control, Act on behalf. These are the core elements of an agency relationship.",
    reference: "Agency Law",
