    educational: "When a seller breaches a contract for the sale of goods, the buyer is entitled to remedies under UCC Article 2. These remedies include cover damages (the difference between the contract price and the cost of replacement goods) and incidental damages (expenses reasonably incurred as a result of the breach). Consequential damages may also be available if they were foreseeable.",
    examTip: "Carefully read the facts to determine if the goods were accepted or rejected. If the goods were rejected, the buyer can 'cover' and recover the difference between the contract price and the cost of cover, plus incidental and consequential damages.",
    memoryAid: "Remember \"CIDE\": Cover damages, Incidental damages, and Consequential damages. These are potential remedies for a buyer when a seller breaches a sales contract.",
    reference: "UCC Article 2",
