    options: ["$60,000","$55,000","$40,000","$45,000"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "The allocation of depreciation to Abigail is valid because it has economic effect. The economic effect test requires that the allocation actually affects the dollar amount a partner receives. Abigail's capital account is $50,000 (beginning) + $0 (50% of income excluding depreciation) - $20,000 (depreciation) = $30,000. Ben's capital account is $50,000 (beginning) + $15,000 (50% of income) = $65,000. The partnership has $10,000 of gain ($90,000 sale price - $80,000 adjusted basis after depreciation). This gain is allocated equally. Abigail's capital account is $30,000 + $5,000 = $35,000. Ben's capital account is $65,000 + $5,000 = $70,000. The partnership has $100,000 cash ($30,000 income + $90,000 sale - $20,000 depreciation) to distribute. The distribution is based on the capital account balances, therefore Abigail will receive $35,000 and Ben will receive $70,000. Ben's capital account at the beginning of the year was $50,000. He received 50% of the $30,000 income or $15,000. His capital account is then $65,000 before the gain. He receives 50% of the $10,000 gain or $5,000. His final capital account is $70,000.\n\nTherefore, Abigail will receive $35,000 from her initial capital account plus 50% of the $10,000 gain, for a total of $40,000 from operations. Because the equipment was sold for $10,000 less than it's original cost, each partner must contribute $5,000 to make up for the loss in value. Thus, the total cash Abigail will receive in liquidation will be $35,000 + $5,000, or $40,000.",
