    difficulty: "hard",
    skillLevel: "Application",
    question: "In 2023, Greg had adjusted gross income (AGI) of $200,000. He contributed stock, which he had held for more than one year, to a public charity. Greg's basis in the stock was $20,000, and its fair market value was $130,000 on the date of the contribution. Greg also made a cash contribution of $20,000 to the same public charity. What is the maximum amount of charitable contribution Greg can deduct in 2023, before considering any carryover?",
    options: ["$120,000","$100,000","$130,000","$150,000"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    explanation: "The stock contribution is generally deductible at fair market value. However, contributions to public charities are limited to 50% of AGI when the contribution consists of capital gain property (stock held for more than one year and if sold at its fair market value would result in long-term capital gain). The cash contribution is limited to 60% of AGI. The deductible amount is the lesser of the actual contributions or the AGI limitations. \n\nStock contribution limitation: $200,000 (AGI) * 0.30 = $60,000\nCash contribution limitation: $200,000 (AGI) * 0.60 = $120,000\n\nSince the stock donation is limited to 30% of AGI, the total deduction is limited to $60,000 (stock) + $20,000 (cash) = $80,000. The stock contribution not deductible in 2023 ($130,000 - $60,000 = $70,000) can be carried forward for up to 5 years. \n\nIf the taxpayer elects to reduce the fair market value of the capital gain property by the amount of gain that would have been long-term capital gain had the property been sold, the 50% AGI limitation can be applied instead. If Greg had elected to reduce the fair market value, the charitable contribution would be $20,000 + $20,000 = $40,000. $200,000 * 50% = $100,000. The deductible amount would be $40,000.\n\nIn this case, the problem is asking what is the maximum amount of charitable contribution Greg can deduct in 2023. In order to maximize the charitable contribution, Greg would not reduce the fair market value of the capital gain property, and therefore, the deduction is $60,000 + $60,000 = $120,000. Because the cash contribution is $20,000, the stock contribution can be $100,000. However, this is limited to $60,000.\n\n$60,000 (stock) + $60,000 (cash) = $120,000",
